05050nam a22008055i 9780814743737DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20062006nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147437377 a10.18574/nyu/97808147437372doi  a(DE-B1597)547869  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a364.10609731 aJacobs, James B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMobsters, Unions, and Feds :bThe Mafia and the American Labor Movement /cJames B. Jacobs. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Acronyms -- t1 Introduction -- t2 Organized Crime and Organized Labor -- t3 President’s Commission on Organized Crime -- t4 Labor Racketeering in New York City -- t5 Organized Labor’s Response to Organized Crime -- t6 Labor Racketeering and the Rank and File -- t7 Attacking Labor Racketeering Prior to Civil RICO (1982) -- t8 Civil RICO Suits and Trusteeships -- t9 The Liberation of IBT Local 560 -- t10 The New York City District Council of Carpenters -- t11 The Four International Unions -- t12 Evaluating Civil RICO -- t13 Concluding Reflections -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNowhere in the world has organized crime infiltrated the labor movement as effectively as in the United States. Yet the government, the AFL-CIO, and the civil liberties community all but ignored the situation for most of the twentieth century. Since 1975, however, the FBI, Department of Justice, and the federal judiciary have relentlessly battled against labor racketeering, even in some of the nation's most powerful unions.Mobsters, Unions, and Feds is the first book to document organized crime's exploitation of organized labor and the massive federal cleanup effort. A renowned criminologist who for twenty years has been assessing the government's attack on the Mafia, James B. Jacobs explains how Cosa Nostra families first gained a foothold in the labor movement, then consolidated their power through patronage, fraud, and violence and finally used this power to become part of the political and economic power structure of Twentieth century urban America.Since FBI Director J. Edgar Hoover's death in 1972, federal law enforcement has aggressively investigated and prosecuted labor racketeers, as well as utilized the civil remedies provided for by the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organization (RICO) statute to impose long-term court-supervised remedial trusteeships on mobbed-up unions. There have been some impressive victories, including substantial progress toward liberating the four most racketeer-ridden national unions from the grip of organized crime, but victory cannot yet be claimed.The only book to investigate how the mob has exploited the American labor movement, Mobsters, Unions, and Feds is the most comprehensive study to date of how labor racketeering evolved and how the government has finally resolved to eradicate it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aFeds.  aMobsters.  aefforts.  aenforcement.  aerase.  aextraordinary.  ainfluence.  alabor.  aleft.  alight.  amafia.  amovement.  ashadow.  asheds.  athat.  aunions.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814743737423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814743737/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backli